ls on the subject, notably the subordination of tariff policy to competition policy and the removal of the firm's right of refusal to sell, both to a degree not previously suggested. The work is infused with his view that the public good takes precedence over the right of the individual to pursue his economic self-interest. "Unless politically courageous decisions are made," he warns, "… our competition policy will continue to be the charade that it now is."  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAntitrust lawxCanada. 0aCommercexRéglementationxCanada. 0aCompetitionxCanada. 0aConcurrencexCanada. 0aIndustrial policyxCanada. 0aOligopoles. 0aOligopolies. 0aPolitique industriellexCanadaxCanada. 0aPricesxCanada. 0aPrixxCanada. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Public Policy / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356062840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773560628423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773560628/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles